            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is portfolio rebalancing?</h2>
              <p>
                Portfolio rebalancing is the process of adjusting your
                investments back to a
                <strong>target asset allocation</strong>. Over time, some assets
                grow faster than others. Without rebalancing, your portfolio can
                drift away from your desired risk level.
              </p>
              <p>
                For example, suppose your target is 60% stocks and 40% bonds.
                After a strong stock market, you might end up at 70% stocks and
                30% bonds. Rebalancing means selling some stocks and buying
                bonds so you return to 60/40.
              </p>

              <h2>How this portfolio rebalancing calculator works</h2>
              <p>This tool helps you:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Compare your <strong>current vs target allocation</strong> for
                  each asset.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Generate a <strong>trade list</strong> (what to buy and sell,
                  and how much).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Estimate <strong>capital gains and tax impact</strong> when
                  you provide cost basis.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Apply a <strong>tolerance band</strong> so you only trade when
                  drift is meaningful.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Key inputs</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Current value</strong> – market value of each asset in
                  your portfolio.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Target %</strong> – desired weight for each asset
                  (should sum to 100%).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Units &amp; cost basis</strong> (optional) – used to
                  estimate realized gains and taxes.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Available cash</strong> – extra money you plan to
                  invest.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Tolerance band</strong> – how far an asset can drift
                  before you rebalance it.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Rebalancing math</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>1. Total portfolio value</strong></p>
                <p>\[ V_{\text{total}} = \sum_i V_i + C \]</p>
                <p>
                  where \(V_i\) is the current value of asset \(i\) and \(C\) is
                  available cash.
                </p>

                <p class="mt-3">
                  <strong>2. Current weight of each asset</strong>
                </p>
                <p>\[ w_i^{\text{current}} = \frac{V_i}{\sum_j V_j} \]</p>

                <p class="mt-3">
                  <strong>3. Target dollar value for each asset</strong>
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ V_i^{\text{target}} = V_{\text{total}} \times
                  \frac{t_i}{100} \]
                </p>
                <p>where \(t_i\) is the target percentage for asset \(i\).</p>

                <p class="mt-3">
                  <strong>4. Trade amount (before tolerance)</strong>
                </p>
                <p>\[ \Delta V_i = V_i^{\text{target}} - V_i \]</p>
                <p>
                  If \(\Delta V_i &gt; 0\), you buy that amount. If \(\Delta V_i
                  &lt; 0\), you sell.
                </p>

                <p class="mt-3"><strong>5. Drift</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Drift}_i = w_i^{\text{current}} - \frac{t_i}{100} \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Practical rebalancing strategies</h2>
              <h3>1. Calendar-based rebalancing</h3>
              <p>
                You rebalance on a fixed schedule (for example annually or
                semi-annually), regardless of how far the portfolio has drifted.
                This is simple and easy to automate.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Threshold-based rebalancing</h3>
              <p>
                You only rebalance when an asset’s weight deviates more than a
                set threshold from target (for example ±5 percentage points).
                This can reduce trading costs and taxes.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Hybrid approach</h3>
              <p>
                Many investors combine both: check the portfolio on a schedule,
                but only trade if drift exceeds a threshold. The tolerance band
                in this calculator lets you model that approach.
              </p>

              <h2>Tax-aware rebalancing tips</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Prefer to rebalance inside
                  <strong>tax-advantaged accounts</strong> (401(k), IRA, ISA,
                  etc.).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use <strong>new contributions and dividends</strong> to move
                  closer to your target without selling.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Be mindful of
                  <strong>short-term vs long-term capital gains</strong> in
                  taxable accounts.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Consider <strong>tax-loss harvesting</strong> when some
                  positions are at a loss.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  The calculator assumes
                  <strong>no transaction fees or bid–ask spreads</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Tax estimates are simplified and based on a single blended
                  rate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It does not account for <strong>wash-sale rules</strong> or
                  country-specific tax nuances.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Rounding may cause small differences between suggested and
                  exact target allocations.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>
              <h3>Is rebalancing always a good idea?</h3>
              <p>
                Rebalancing is generally recommended for long-term investors to
                keep risk in line with their goals. However, if trading costs or
                taxes are very high relative to the amount of drift, it can be
                better to wait or rebalance more gradually.
              </p>

              <h3>What if my target percentages don’t add up to 100%?</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator will warn you. Adjust your targets so they sum to
                100%, or treat cash as its own asset class with a target
                percentage.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Can I use this for ETFs, mutual funds, and individual stocks?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Yes. You can treat each ETF, mutual fund, or stock as a separate
                asset, or group similar holdings into broader buckets (for
                example “US stocks”, “International stocks”, “Bonds”).
              </p>
